title: For Sale:  Mossberg Model 500 10 Millionth Commemorative, Serial Number U500005
postcontent: Shooting Industry Masters Auction Benefiting First Shots More than 350 industry representatives, ranging from top administrators and factory personnel to professional shooters, will compete in the 2013 Shooting Industry Masters shooting competition July 19-20 at the Cody Shooting Complex near Cody, Wyoming. A major component of the shoot will be fundraising events to benefit the National Shooting Sports Foundation (NSSF) First Shots program, which introduces thousands of new shooters to the shooting sports each year. You can bid on this highly collectible Mossberg shotgun — and help support this important program — only at Gunbroker.com! History Since the first model came off the line on August, 21, 1961, the Mossberg 500 Pump-Action shotgun has received accolades from sportsmen and women, law enforcement and military personnel alike for its reliability, versatility and affordability; and notably for its distinctive ambidextrous top-mounted safety. Now this true American classic has reached an astonishing milestone of 10,000,000 produced; and in an unprecedented 52 years making the 500 Pump-Action the fastest-selling shotgun in history! Lead design engineer, Carl Benson, and his team at O.F. Mossberg & Sons, Inc. began work on a slide-action shotgun to replace the unique design of the 200 Series which had been in production since 1955. Though the Model 200 had set a new standard for innovation, Benson knew that Mossberg needed a more traditional-looking pump shotgun to compete with the “big three” at the time. The result was the 500 Shooting System, a 12-gauge pump-action base gun with interchangeable barrels. Features of those early Model 500 shotguns included the top-of-the-receiver safety; disconnecting trigger; damascened bolts; single slide-bar; solid steel-to-steel lock-up of the bolt to the barrel; and anodized aluminum receiver for lighter weight and better balance. This original design remained virtually unchanged for 30-plus years. Sixteen and 20-gauge versions were added to the 500 line-up in 1963 and the .410 bore became available in 1965. Over the years, numerous configurations designed for Law Enforcement, Military and Conservation groups were introduced as well as special purpose configurations. Youth models made their first appearance in 1983. In total, over 10 million Model 500 pump-action shotguns have been produced. To commemorate this historic benchmark, Mossberg donated the heavily-embellished 10 Millionth 500 with serial #U500000 to the NRA® National Firearms Museum in recognition of the National Rifle Association’s unwavering defense of the Second Amendment. Mossberg has also produced ten additional “10 Millionth” commemorative shotguns with the unique serialization of U500001 through U500010 for the fundraising efforts of deserving industry partners. Serial #U500004 was given to NRA-ILA® for their auction at the 2013 NRA Annual Meeting & Exhibits in Houston, Texas. Our featured “10 Millionth” Model 500 here is serial number U500005 and obviously is a bench-mark, showcasing Mossberg’s manufacturing and embellishment expertise. This is a one-time-only very special series and will never be available again. These milestone-commemorative Mossberg 500 shotguns feature a matte-silver finished receiver with gold inlay; traditionally-styled, high-gloss Fancy Walnut stock and forend with fine checkering on the pistol grip and wrapping around the underside of the forend; and classic red recoil pad with white Pachmayr line spacer. Distinctive jeweled bolt and elevator; gold trigger; 28-inch ported, vent rib barrel; and complementing high polished blue metal finish on exposed metalwork complete these classic pump-actions

In 1961, Grady & Ann Phillips opened “The Sport and Hobby Shop” in an 840 sf vacancy in the Pruitt Shopping Center in Anderson, SC. This store stocked model cars, fishing supplies, athletic goods and a total of two guns. Growth came quickly and in 1963, the store was moved 3 doors down in the shopping center to a 1,400 sf location. Here Grady and Ann added more firearms, toys, games and even Barbie Dolls!

As the business continued to grow, it was moved in 1965 to a 2,400 sf building in the then-new Belvedere Plaza Shopping Center. Horseback riding equipment, western wear and more toys and hobbies were added to the inventory. The name was also changed to “Grady’s Sport Shop” – a name by which some people still refer to us today.

In 1969, Grady and Ann decided to focus on the core business – hunting and fishing. The store was moved one door down in the Belvedere Plaza to a 3,600 sf location. The variety of hunting and fishing equipment was expanded and a mail-order division was started. Grady began producing direct-mail flyers which are still our most effective form of advertising today.

Explosive growth came in the early 70's and the store was moved 3 doors down in the Belvedere Plaza to a 7,000 sf building – almost double the size of the previous location. 10 years later, Grady and Ann felt that a free-standing building would best serve our customers. Property was secured in our current location and a 9,800 sf building was constructed. The name was also changed to “Grady’s Great Outdoors” at this time.

Over the last 22 years, the original structure has been expanded and remodeled to its current 19,000+ sf size.

Our current line-up of products includes: Hunting, Fishing, Camping, Kayaks & Canoes, Casual & Work Clothing, Casual & Work Footwear and much more!! We carry virtually all of the major brands as well as many hard-to-find specialty items.

Grady’s Great Outdoors continues to be owned and operated by the Phillips Family. We cannot express how much we appreciate the support of our customers over the last 50 years. We look forward to serving you for the next 50 years!

This is an incredibly accurate, full power 44 Mag., lead free load. The long-for-weight all copper bullet uses up the limited powder capacity of the case and keeps us from driving the bullet any faster than we are currently doing.

This 44 mag. load will work great and give adequate penetration for hunting big game species up to about 350 lbs. Since the bullet weight is relatively light, this load only generates moderate recoil.

At Buffalo Bore we always use real over-the-counter firearms to develop our published velocities. title: For Trade:  1942 Izhevsk Ex Sniper Mosin Nagant & CZ 24 pistol
postcontent:
I have for trade a rifle and pistol. 

First is a 1942 Izhevsk 91/30 ex sniper. This is the hardest to find of the ex snipers or sniper rifles. Was a side mount PEM set up. Arsenal refinished, was put back into a war time stock, numbers matching, no line outs, bolt changed and matches. Bore frosted but not counterbored and shoots excellent. Still a tack driver. Comes with sling and bayonet, cleaning kit. Has scope numbers on side of barrel and has plugged holes where the PEM side mount was on reciever. This is the rarer PEM, not the more common PU set up. The majority of sniper rifles used by the greats you read about were PEM. Battle of Stalingrad the majority were PEMs which stalingrad started 42.

Second is a CZ 24 pistol in 380. Made in 1937 and has the czech military acceptance proof of J with lion and 37. Has original grips, it is numbers matching complete, even magazine matches. Bore shines and is excellent. Was a pre war high polish finish pistol that still looks nice. After germany invaded czechoslovakia they issued these captured pistols to the SS and wermacht. 

Both of these firearms are a nice piece of WWII history and collectible. 

You can call or text me at REDACTED anytime up till midight. I live central wisconsin and can meet you in Mauston, New Lisbon, Tomah or Stevens Point, or Wisconsin Rapids.

title: For Sale/Trade:  Best offer on advice
postcontent: Egyptian Maadi AK47s used to be  pawn shop rifles....surplus.....$350-400.  Just like the AMD-65 $400-450.  Depending on manufacture and dates, these were best you could do rifles for those who couldn't afford quality, or didn't buy quality before importation got cut off.  Surplus is defined as those rifles sold by the pallet.....average.  You might get a decent shooter, or you might get a lemon.  For the price, it seemed to be a decent gamble.  Now...they are apparently "rare" and "hard to find".  Quite frankly.....just about everything is hard to find these days.  Damned if stuff aint coming out of closets once forgotten at a price that might feed your family for three months or make two house payments.  You youngsters need to be up on your game.  Take this from an old guy that's been in the firearms market for the past 25 years and in the military to boot.  You can buy a quality AK47 made in USA for less than that surplus rifle now.  You think ammo costs too much now?  In reality it's still pretty cheap considering the supply and demand and world market.  If you're willing to pay double what a rifle is actually worth....you're feeding the machine and those who are wanting to take advantage of you and your family, just like those who gouged on gasoline prices after 9-11.  Never forget folks.  Bottom feeders, bottom rifles....bottom line.  You make your own decisions at this point.  Just do your research first.  It's too bad some of you willing to buy now didn't have the chance to buy quality when it was available at face value.  I understand most of you were still in school.  Well..........learning is good.......school's out.  Best of luck selling and buying.  Remember one thing in your dealings......buyer or seller........no remorse.  be that as it may.  Zastava my ass.  Put two and two together.....Zastava and Egyptian?  Russian blueprints to boot.  Do the math kids.
